column3: There are many different elements of an ideal tragedy described within the passage.  First, how a tragedy should be arranged not on a simple but on a complex plan, consisting perhaps of multiple plots. Second, how a tragedy  should imitate actions that display pity and fear. Third, how a tragedy should involve a change of fortune from good and bad. This misfortune should be brought about by some error of judgement or fratility by a character who is renowned, but not eminently good or bad. Finally, a tragedy should not have a happy ending. These are some of the things that make up an ideal tragedy described by Aristotle.
column4: "An ideal tragedy, as described by Aristotle, is characterized by complexity and meticulous planning. It should exhibit elements of both direct and implied pity and fear, emphasizing the character's emotional state. Additionally, the story should feature a shift in circumstances from good to bad, often resulting from an error of judgment or flaw. The ending should lack a happy resolution, underscoring the tragedy's overall tragic nature."

column3: There were various things that the factory would do to cover up and essentially use the spoiled meat that they had. One manner in which they practiced this was by rubbing the meat with soda to take away the smell, as stated in paragraph two.  The workers would also pickle their meat to get rid of the odor but if it was very pungent, they had a second and much stronger pickle which helped destroy the smell, which the workers called, "giving them thirty per cent." Along with this, they would label the packages in many ways to make it look like it was "original" even if they were made out of meat parts that were not supposed to be used. Another form in which they would use and cover-up spoiled meat would be by getting spoiled whole ham and old sausage with mold from Europe and dosing it with borax and glycerin, where it would then be dumped into hoppers and made over again for packaging. Mice, feces, poisoned bread, dirt, diseases, and sawdust were just a few things that would be processed in the hoppers along with the spoiled meat. Lastly, they would also use their chemistry department to make sausages appear brown-with the use of borax and colored gelatin- and labeled it "smoked" sausage after their practice of smoking sausage became expensive for the factory.  In all, the actions in which the factory practiced were extremely unsanitary and do not appear today thanks to the Meat Inspection Act.
column4: Sure, here is the rewritten passage:  "The factory employed various methods to conceal and misuse spoiled meat. One tactic involved rubbing the meat with soda to eliminate its odor. Another method, employed when the smell was particularly pungent, was to pickle the meat, using a potent solution to destroy the odor. Packages were labeled in a misleading manner, showcasing originality, although they were often crafted from spoiled meat parts. Other practices included altering the color of the meat by using borax solution and adding colored gelatin, simulating the texture and appearance of naturally aged sausage. Additionally, mice, fecal matter, contaminated bread, dirt, diseases, and sawdust were processed within hoppers alongside the spoiled meat. Finally, the factory utilized their chemistry department to create sausages that resembled brown-aged ones, deceiving customers who were accustomed to the authentic, expensive look of traditionally smoked sausages."

column3: Ron Jones, a high school teacher, found himself unable to explain to students how people often followed the crowd throughout history, even when bad things were happening.  He decided to demonstrate it to his students though an experiment called the third wave. The experiment started out well with drastic improvement in the students academic skills, so Jones gave instructions to his students on how to recruit new members. It quickly spread throughout the school,” by the end of the day the movement had over 200 participants”(3). In just three days the experiment went from 30 students to 200, clearly the students were devoted and eager to join this project. The students were so loyal to this project that they would report to Jones if another student failed to abide by the rules.  Jones began to feel like the experiment was working a bit too well and feared it was getting out of control. The reader is shown this when, “the students became increasingly involved in the project and their discipline and loyalty to the project was so outstanding that Jones felt it was slipping out of control”(4).  Jones began to feel that the experiment was getting out of hand so he decided to reveal to his students that it was an experiment.

column3: An ideal tragedy, according to Aristotle, has many imporant elements, but three main ones. First, the main character must be a good and relatable figure that has suffered or done something terrible. This is because the audience will connect with the character more, as opposed to a bad character, and more likely to feel fear or pity at their inevitable fate. Next, the plot itself has to go from good to bad. This is a well-constructed plot and  hits the audience strongly. This ties into the last element, a tragic ending. The best tragedies have to end with the character ending unhappy or in a bad situation. This has the most effect on the audience.

Finally, the ending should be tragic and leave the audience with a sense of sadness and disappointment."

column3: The Third Wave was an experiment that was developed by a history teacher named Ron Jones. It took place at a high school he taught at called, Cubberley High School in Palo Alto in California during the first week of April in 1967. The experiment was a demonstation of how people followed crowds even when terrible things were happening.  Jones developed an authoritative dictatorship in his classroom to teach students about the German mentality. He made rules in his classroom such as; students had to stand up when asking or answering questions, students had to answer in three words, and students should salute each other in and out of school. On the forth day, Jones ended the experiment when he felt it was slipping out of his control. This shows that the students had become extremly involved in this experiment that they caused it to go out of control.
column4: The Third Wave was an experiment conducted by Ron Jones, a history teacher, in his classroom at Cubberley High School in Palo Alto, California, during the first week of April in 1967. Jones created an atmosphere of authoritarian rule within his classroom, instructing students to stand up and answer his questions or face punishment. The students were given strict rules such as standing up when speaking, answering in three words, and saluting each other appropriately. As the experiment progressed, Jones became increasingly frustrated with the students' unwavering adherence to the rules he had established. The overwhelming power of the students' disciplined involvement led him to curtail the experiment, highlighting the profound consequences when individuals become engrossed in an activity.
